Believe it or not this adorable home came from a kit! This is one of Washington DC’s many Sears Kit homes and was built in 1929. Available for purchase by catalog, building materials for each home were shipped via railroad and could be built in as little as 90 days. 

More about the DC “Gingerbread House” via @washingtonpost: https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/where-we-live/wp/2016/09/09/a-cleveland-park-gingerbread-house-is-for-sale-for-the-first-

Trees to please 🎀🎄 Haute holidays at the Hillwood Museum features beautiful trees and decorations inspired by the special exhibition Grace of Monaco: Princess in Dior. 

My favorite one of them all is the one in the 2 first slides - a tree inspired by the dress Grace Kelly wore to a the Mycca Gala in 1970 and the Cannes Film Festival in 1972. But of course all of them are gorgeous and you have them for yourself! For more info please visit @hillwoodmuseum ☺️

2022 was the year of…

Fewer photos, but better memories. Of ruthlessly editing my life and everything in it. Of “if it’s not a hell yes, it’s a hell no.” 

In 2022, I started a new job that really spoke to my values and priorities. I took some time away from Instagram when I needed it. I got into a consistent workout routine and therapy schedule. 

Each of these choices was made out of a newer, deeper knowing of myself. A knowing made by leaning in close and listening to my own whispers, visions and dreams.

So here’s to the year that was. And cheers to 2023 and everything to come. IG friends near and far: thanks for reminding me that when you get to where you’re going, it’s you and the people who support you who got you there. Goodnight!

#2022inreview #2022bestof #photographersofinstagram

Dare I say that I am thriving this January? 🤔 Usually this month is brutal on my mental health but for some reason the "Monday" of this year feels... different. Some potential reasons:

📆 Making plans for the year. I am taking the initiative and hitting "book" on fun travel plans, restaurant reservations, plans with friends, events, and more. I just booked a trip to Nantucket (my first time!) and am looking forward to an Alaska cruise with my family over the summer.

🏃🏼‍♀️ Staying busy. Between work and social plans I am getting out of the house this month. Sorry, cold weather, you can't keep me inside anymore.

🍹 Seeing all the conversation about dry January. Many people are exploring sobriety and thinking hard about how alcohol impacts them. I personally transitioned to a no/low-alcohol lifestyle about 8 years ago and haven't looked back. I feel like it's finally becoming normalized - and I feel relieved and less alone in my choice to not drink.

It was during his 1960 presidential campaign and Kennedy went to his inauguration from this home in January 1961. #georgetowndc #historyfacts #historicarchitecture #dchistory

“I feel so intensely the delights of shutting oneself up in a little world of one’s own, with pictures and music and everything beautiful.” - Virginia Woolf 

@whatstacydid posted some wonderful photos and this quote the other day and it really resonated with me. I love to spend time in editing mode imagining the stories of the people who live in these homes and spaces. 

What do you think their daily lives are like? Home is where we feel safe to feel our strongest emotions and spill our secrets to loved ones, or to no one. I wonder what stories lie within?

Allow me to reintroduce myself - my name is Jane! 👋🏻 I started this account posting photos of houses in the historic neighborhoods near me as a way to learn about photography. I took a class on DSLR photography, then another class in the “field” which happened to be one of my favorite places, Old Town Alexandria. I’ve always loved architecture and design so I started photographing and posting pictures of homes and streets all throughout the DC area.

If there’s something you’re passionate about, Instagram is a great place to share and connect with others who love the same thing. ❤️💙

And I hear that photos are BACK on this platform — yay!

Inspiration for the next time you’re in the mood for a getaway: Williamsburg, Virginia. Just a 2.5 hour drive from the DC area, it’s the perfect destination for a long weekend away and I can’t wait for my next trip back. So many great restaurants, cafes, museums and things to do. 
 
And, the architecture of Colonial Williamsburg is incredible. I recommend dedicating an entire day just to wandering around the area and soaking it all in. Yorktown is also a must-see if you’re into 18th-century architecture and is the site of where America’s independence was won by George Washington. 
 
Get inspired to plan your own Williamsburg experience when you visit the new #ChooseYourPace experience near the Capital One Arena. Check out my stories for more info!

Why is it that success is judged differently for women? It's all too common to see my talents diminished to "a trick rather than a skill and a craft" (borrowing the words of Taylor Swift). I was once accused of buying followers and buying engagement (100% false by the way) and guess what? My talents are not a fluke or a stroke of luck, and can't be reduced to some sort of trick. My tolerance and patience has been worn out seeing talented friends and women in my life belittled, reduced and minimized. 

I'll pass along some advice that amazing women (including Taylor Swift) have given - keep making your art. Keep doing your thing. There will be criticism. Take that as a sign that you're doing something right. 💪🏻

Wishing you a very merry cherry blossom season 🍒🌸

To my friends and followers beyond DC - these blooms are a big deal. There's a buzz in the air right now as the cherry trees near the Tidal Basin approach "peak bloom" and it's a time where DC welcomes many, many visitors from out of town. Maybe you visited during a school trip or a weekend getaway - but it's a really special time to be in town.

I live "across the river" from DC in Arlington, Virginia but took a longgg walk the other night involving a bridge and many steps to capture some photos of these blooms. Hope you enjoy! ❤️

Do you know the story of these three houses on Charleston’s Meeting St.? 

These homes are known as the Three Sisters. Some say the name comes from the hair color of each of the three sisters that lived there. In reality the nickname comes from their similar architectural styles. 💚💗⭐️

Charleston’s famous Pink House deserved its own spot on my feed 💗 It’s over 300 years old but still a gem in my mind. 

Small but resilient to decades of fires, hurricanes and hot summers, you can find it on one of the city’s few remaining cobblestones streets at 📍17 Chalmers St. 

#CharlestonSC #CharlestonFrenchQuarter #PinkCharlestonHouse

The world I want to show you is a bit different than what might be considered “popular” on social media. But I think old places are just as worthy of our love and attention as shiny new ones. ❤️

📍This is Philadelphia Alley in Charleston’s historic French Quarter District and dates back to 1776. It was once known as Duelers Alley, and it played host to duels when they were a popular way to settle disputes. Some say that the spirits of the duelists who lost remain to haunt the alley.

Welcome to Dumbarton Oaks, a historic estate in Washington, DC’s Georgetown neighborhood. 🍃 It was once the residence and garden of a U.S. diplomat and his wife, and is now home to a research library and museum. 

It’s also one of my happy places in DC and somewhere I visit every season to admire its many moods and colors. Is your happy place a garden? Or is it somewhere else?

This is a must-do if you are visiting DC. During the winter season, admission to the @dumbartonoaks gardens is free and no tickets are required. During the regular season, which runs March 15-October 31, daily tickets are $7 and required. The gardens are open Tuesday-Sunday from 2-6 pm. 💚

Of course this isn’t the only secret to living here. Once you are able to get the important things right, this just makes life here a little sweeter.

If you haven’t visited @hillwoodmuseum, this is your sign to pay this incredible estate a visit. 💚

Set on over 25 acres, Hillwood Estate, Museum and Gardens was once the home of collector, businesswoman and philanthropist Marjorie Merriweather Post. Her mansion is now a spectacular museum with an extensive collection of Russian and French decorative arts. The estate also boasts 13 acres of gardens including a rose garden, French Parterre, Japanese-style garden and a greenhouse.

I would dedicate at least an hour and a half to exploring the entire estate, and even more time to take in the little details on the beautiful collection of art and featured exhibits.

Less than a 45 minute drive from DC, this is a beautiful burg with a historic downtown filled with boutiques, restaurants and coffee shops. Here’s how you can make a great weekend visit:

☕️Get some caffiene at the small-batch roastery Goosecup (@goosecup) in downtown Leesburg. I tried one of their seasonal drinks and it was out of this world.

🚙Hit up Old Lucketts Store (@luckettstore) to hunt for antiques, home decor, and more. If I had to decorate a house from scratch this is where I would head to find everything! 

🪴Visit Garden Gatherings (@gardengatherings) at the Old Lucketts Store to add something beautiful to your plant collection. 

🎃Then, it’s time for farm stands! Some good ones that area always well-stocked are Loudonberry (@loudounberry), Brossman (@brossmanfarmstand), and Farmer John’s Market. 

🥪Make your way over to downtown Leesburg to get lunch (I love Cowbell Kitchen @cowbellkitchen for the best sandwiches and they have a ton of gluten free items if you’re into that) and do some shopping in the beautiful little boutiques that line the street. A few favorite stores include 27 South (@27southinteriors), Muz & Rose (@muzandrose) and wldwst (@wld_wst).

🏠If historic homes are your thing (they definitely are mine!) then visit Oatlands Historic House and Gardens (@oatlands.historic.house). You can either purchase a $10 grounds pass to walk around the 400 acres, or stop by for a walk-in tour that includes access to the house, held every Friday, Saturday and Sunday at 11AM, 12PM and 2PM.

🏞️Book The Cottage at Forest Hills Farm nestled close to vineyards but less than 10 minutes to downtown Leesburg for the coziest stay. Wake up to fresh air, 4 pastures and say hello to the farm animals before and after your days of exploring.

📌Be sure to SAVE this Reel for planning!

Looking for a cozy getaway to Virginia’s countryside? Look no further than @bluerockvirginia, a gorgeous “country chic” property set on over 80 acres in Rappahannock County right near the Blue Ridge Mountains. 

Here are just a few reasons to add this 5-star property to your list:

1️⃣The food! Former Pineapple & Pearls head chef Bin Lu has created a spectacular four-course tasting menu to enjoy while admiring the inn’s bucolic views. The menu changes with the seasons, and ours featured sweet corn agnolotti, grilled striploin and special add-ons like buckwheat parker house rolls, wedge salad and ice cream with champagne. Cheers to that!

2️⃣ The inn features 5 distinctive rooms with luxurious amentites like Molton Brown bath products, Parachute linen bedding, and Nespresso machines. A delicious breakfast is included with your room rate, which can be enjoyed either in your room or in the dining area.

3️⃣The inn has a prime location right in the heart of Rappahannock County, located just a 15-minute drive from the famous Skyline Drive with scenic views of the Blue Ridge Mountains. It’s also located close to the historic towns of Sperryville and Washington which are home to cute cafes, farm stands, boutique shops, and vineyards that you can enjoy during your weekend getaway.

The inn has very limited availability for the next few months, so I would book your stay ASAP! Room rates vary from $379 to $499 per night. The four-course tasting menu is $119/pp with optional wine parings at $79/pp.

If wineries, mountain vistas, and exceptional restaurants are your vibe, you’ll want to give this area a visit. And with the fall foliage starting to turn, there are few better places to enjoy the splendor of the season. Here are my top recommendations:

🏡Stay at @bluerockvirginia
🥪Lunch at Before & After Cafe in Sperryville
🍃Shop at @wildroots_apothecary
⛰️Visit @shenandoahnps’ famous Skyline Drive, and you can access it via the Thornton Gap entrance just 15 mins from Blue Rock Inn
🍎Pop by Thornton River Orchard for seasonal goodies
🍴Grab coffee and then lunch at Patty O’s in Washington, VA

The new Autumn Clock Tower Tea at the Waldorf Astoria in DC has to be the most fun way to celebrate Fall. My friend and I started our experience with glasses of champagne, then chose from the selection of premium Rishi teas - our favorite was the cinnamon plum. Next up came the tea sandwiches, scones and sweet treats - served on a gorgeous three tier display - each one was delicious and made with seasonal ingredients like figs, pumpkin, apple and cranberry. They also have gluten free options too for the people avoiding gluten in your life (or yourself!)

You have to check out this afternoon tea at @waldorfastoriadc! Price for the tea is $105/pp. Seatings are Friday, Saturday and Sunday at 12 PM and 2 PM.
